A3. Advanced notes: Scientific and Numerical Python¶

A3.1 Pulling Compressed netCDF Files¶

x
 
 

Sometimes, such as when we want to pull data from netCDF files from some data site such as http://www.globalbedo.org, we might find that 'older style' formats have been used, such as netCDF3 which might not have internal compression.

To save storage space, it is common to compress such files extrenally (i.e. to gzip a file).

That makes direct reading from a url a bit more tricky, and in such cases, we may as well uncompress the file to a local temporary file.

x
 
 

Doing this in Python¶

x
 
 

What we are going to do is to write a class to download a gzipped file from a url and return a filename that can be read by other functions.

The file is available as gzurl.py, in the directory files/python.

To be able to import this, we have to put files/python in the path where Python looks for modules:

import sys,os

# i.e. where we look for modules
sys.path.insert(0,os.path.abspath('files%spython')%os.sep)
 
from gzurl import gzurl

Next, we need to write these data to a file. In this case, we don't want to really save the data anywhere, so we want to use a temporary file.

In Python, you can create a temporary file using the module tempfile, which creates a temporary (unique) file on the system.

We could try, for instance to build a mask for these, supposing them to be some other 'invalid' number, but in this dataset, we have some other data layers that can help:

The NIR data, in particular, seem to have these odd 'edge effects', which are probably negative reflectance values, and this clearly isn't taken out by using the data mask.

Thats useful, but we need to combine masks.

Let's first reconsider the Data_Mask.

x
 
 

The mask has value 1 where we want data and 0 elsewhere.

Above, we made a negated mask by using:

mask = np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']) == 0

If we were to convert the mask first to bool, this would be True where we want data and False where we don't.

To form a data mask for the masked array, we want it set to False where the data are valid ...

so it would be clearer if we used a not operation on the array.

We might suppose this is:

In [267]:
mask = not np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
mask = not np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
 
 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ValueError                                Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-267-40b253bbb70a> in <module>()
----> 1 mask = not np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)

ValueError: The truth value of an array with more than one element is ambiguous. Use a.any() or a.all()
. . .
x
 
 

but we see that for numpy arrays, this is not the way to do it.

Instead, we can use bitwise operators:

  • ~ : not
  • & : and
  • | : or

or instead use numpy functions np.logical_not(), np.logical_and(), np.logical_or().

Practically, bitwise operators are more compact, and in many ways clearer, so:

In [268]:
mask = ~ np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
mask = ~ np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
 
 
. . .
x
 
 

To combine the masks then, we could form (e.g. 3) masks.

What logic do we want though?

It's probably easiest to think about that if we make all of the masks True where we want data:

In [271]:
# True where we want data
# True where we want data
mask1 = np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
mask2 = np.array(nc.variables['DHR_VIS']) > 0
mask3 = np.array(nc.variables['DHR_NIR']) > 0
 
 
. . .
x
 
 

Then it should be quite obvious that and and combination of these will be True where we want data.

To get the mask for the masked array, we have to then negate that, so:

In [272]:
mask = ~ (mask1 & mask2 & mask3)
mask = ~ (mask1 & mask2 & mask3)
 
 
. . .
x
 
 

Although the 'fill' value is supposed to be nan here, we find instead that it is 0.0 (it is nan only in the 0.5 degree product!) ... considering that, we probably want to threshold on the Weighted_Number_of_Samples field as well (remembering that we want it False for valid data):

In [273]:
# True where we want data
# True where we want data
mask1 = np.array(nc.variables['Data_Mask']).astype(bool)
mask2 = np.array(nc.variables['DHR_VIS']) > 0
mask3 = np.array(nc.variables['DHR_NIR']) > 0
mask4 = np.array(nc.variables['Weighted_Number_of_Samples']) > 0.5
 
mask = ~ (mask1 & mask2 & mask3 & mask4)
 
plt.figure(figsize=(14,14))
plt.title('weighted number of samples')
# convert to normal numpy array and multiply by mask to show this
plt.imshow(np.array(data['Weighted_Number_of_Samples']) * ~ mask,interpolation='none')
plt.colorbar()
